If you zoom in you can see 3 scars on the left side of my body. There’s 3 more to match on the other side. 7 of my scars are visible. There’s many others you can’t see. Those are deeper, more painful to talk about. The ones on the surface are from years of trying to shrink. Trauma from existing in a bigger body. A tummy tuck to remove excess skin postpartum. Skin excisions on both thighs to reduce the size of my ample hips. Skin removal on my backside to make it fit a smaller body I had managed to diet myself into. To be honest I wouldn’t mind getting another surgery to remove skin from my inner thighs and arms - consequence of years of yo-yo dieting and being told that existing in my body as it is, is wrong. I sometimes catch myself wondering if I’d be better off not subjecting myself to this electivemutilation process. But then I’d would have had to go back in time to when society, my parents, my environment and even people who were supposed to be my friends started harassing me just for being the shape I am. The healing would’ve had to start there. Maybe had I not experienced all these things I wouldn’t be here talking to such a wide group of people that support my body for what it is.  Relearning confidence. Self acceptance. Radical love. And if my journey can be of help to someone else - to encourage them to find beauty and self acceptance within, then all of this would’ve already been worth it.
🤎

I discovered my love for climbing in 2014. I had moved to Nevada for work and learned quickly that Las Vegas houses some world renowned climbing rocks. I rented a place in Summerlin and spent a lot of time exploring those Red Rocks. Prior to that experience, I had never gone rock climbing. I had never seen someone with a bigger body like mine doing it. I didn’t think it would be a sport for a curvy shaped person. Climbers are usually toned with little body fat, but my kid wanted to try something new and climbing gyms looked like an adult sized playground so I decided to give it a go. We went climbing so frequently that we got a membership to the local indoor gym and when weather permitted, we went to play in the red rocks too. Fast forward to 2023 and I can tell you this - I’m still the largest body in a climbing gym but I still have so much fun! I’m not an expert or technical climber at all- and I am far from being in a strong body at this point (pictures 1 and 2 are from when I started in 2014 and prob my lightest weight as an adult) but I can tell you that I smiled the entire time. I am a little sore today from lack of practice but pushing myself back to doing things I love is absolutely worth with it 🧗‍♀️
Now let’s see if I get back into cycling and maybe Brazilian jiu-jitsu . 
🚩I am aware this won’t be my most popular post, because many of you come for photos of my hair, but if this gets you off the couch and into an activity that you love, then it’s totally worth the lower engagement to me!

When I started my undergraduate education in the USA I had no idea what a GPA(grade point average)was. I was never a dedicated student in Brasil. I had mastered a system which allowed me to show up for class on exam days and score the bare minimum to pass. The rest of the time, you could find me soaking up the rays at the beach. I’d leave and arrive home at the same time wearing my uniform to avoid suspicion, but underneath the jeans and school shirt, I had on a swimsuit and the occasional left over sand from the beach 🌊🙈
 School just wasn’t stimulating enough, the teachers would have us waste our precious time perfunctorily coping down lectures they had pasted onto the board from old decrepit books. There was never a discussion. No talking was allowed. Our questions were hardly addressed. I felt stifled, anesthetized. So I walked to the beach instead. I watched the surfers wait for the sets to swell up, watched the rise and fall of the tides, followed the little creatures that crawled through the hot sand until they disappeared. I treasured every moment of freedom away from the walls of what felt like an oppressive institution.
Somehow, miraculously, I managed to graduate high school (early) and be accepted into 6 of the 7 Universities I applied to.  And from then on I continued onto to finish a Master’s and a Ph.D. 🎓
I was too young in my teens to fully understand how my rebellion and visceral search for freedom and autonomy would play out in my adult life but when I look back I can see how I had already started to sow the seeds that paved the way for who I am today. 
And I love how complex, strange but utterly beautiful this journey has been. If you read all the way to the end, I thank you for indulging me on this platform. Somehow I feel at home here too.  I hope you do as well.

Much love and light 💡

The judgement we cast in others is but a mere reflection of our own pain. When you begin the difficult process of learning to love yourself, you begin looking at everything around you with kinder eyes. So when people come at me with mean hateful comments all I see is a reflection of their deep suffering. As a matter of fact, that’s what most people around us see: someone who is hurting and therefore feels the need to hurt others. The work of Marshall Rosenberg, another visionary who left us too soon, helped me filter out the judgment and simply hear requests. Marshall called this trading jackal for giraffe ears. “Giraffes” listen for what’s underneath the pain. What the true question is and respond accordingly. It’s very hard to do this when you grow up surrounded by criticism, but the liberation from this practice is incredible. Have you ever heard of this work? The official name is non-violent communication. It’s incredibly powerful.
Much love and light 💡

The algorithm rewards consistency. There’s no magic. Sometimes there’s a tiny bit of luck when finding an otherwise unknown niche (I feel like I sorta stumbled upon it) but apart from that, it’s a simple formula. That’s why it is critical to enjoy the process, or people don’t stay the course.  They get tired. They burn out. Because the obstacles come at you from left field. Copy cat accounts (there’s over 400 using my name and photos), trolls who haven’t found love deep inside so they unleash their pain onto you, jealousy and a small percentage of dedicated haters. People who for whatever reason decide to pick you for a target. There’s the internal obstacles too - the quotidian stuff. Inspiration, creativity, mood, location, outfits, etc.  Those are easier to circumvent because when you become more vulnerable you can even share about them. But yeah, being passionately dedicated to the craft in addition to diligence, are the necessary ingredients for growth in this social media platform.
I had a phone conversation with an entrepreneur a few months ago who was baffled at the sheer size of my page. I sensed in his tone that someone who presents like me shouldn’t be as successful as I am, but what he didn’t fully grasp was my tenacity and understanding of these mechanisms. And so here I am, still growing and producing content nearly 5 years after I started as an anonymous account. And for as long as y’all will put up with me and my hair 💅, I will keep taking photos, reels and sharing tidbits of this wonderful  journey with you 🤍

Part 1/3
Did I ever tell you the story of how I ended up in a yellow cab in Fez, Morocco, using my elementary French (merci alliance française) to save my life ? It’s a long one but here we go:
I was freshly single post-divorce and this Russian man (that’s what we gonna call him) was infatuated enough with me to fly my mom from Rio to Miami to watch my kid so we could visit two countries of my choice, Spain and Morocco. He seemed adventurous and intriguing enough, so I agreed to this crazy date idea. After a few days touring Madrid, Toledo, Cordoba, and Granada, Spain, we ferried over to Tangier in Morocco to catch a train to our final destination, Fez. We had woken up ung’dly early to make the crossing from Europe to Africa and did not have a minute to exchange euros for dirhams or have breakfast. We barely made it onto the train that had already left the station when we realized we didn’t have the right currency to pay for the tickets. Luckily, I was able to ask the kind people next to me if they would like to buy some euros, in my very rusty French since I don’t speak Arabic, to which they thankfully agreed. I had no idea what the exchange rate was but I was beyond grateful to have tickets ready before the attendant walked through collecting them. The ride was long and ricketed, the view was beautiful between the coast and the desert. The people on the train were kind and shared their food when they noticed I didn’t have enough dirham left over from the ticket to buy a snack and even the chickens sitting in the aisle next to mine seemed well behaved. The only issue was the bathroom in the train. I had been drinking water all morning but when I noticed that the toilet was a hole in the shaky stall I decided to hold it till we arrived at the station. Apparently I wasn’t the only one holding things in, a mass exodus from the train descended into a beeline for the bathrooms at the station. Relieved to have finally arrived at our final city with an empty bladder and eager to explore this new country, I went to look for my date. He was half-way through the main lobby looking ghostly when he spotted me and whispered under his breath: run! 
(To be continued 😉)

Part 2/3
Run? WTF do you mean RUN? I asked, my face turning red. Cited as the oldest city in the country, a UNESCO heritage center,  home to the world's first university, an incredible medina and the famous leather tanneries,  Fez is where I lost my cool with the Russian. The thing about me is that I had to adult at a very young age and for the first time I was looking forward to relinquishing responsibilities to someone I thought could handle travel plans. The fact that he booked a ferry crossing for 8 AM meant we had to wake up at 5, drive to the port nearly 1:30 hrs away without getting lost, find parking and be in line to board by 7 AM.  Not exactly my type of romantic vacation. When we finally made it through the strait of Gibraltar,  I realized I’d have to handle a lot more than I signed up for. As we exited the port, the Russian jumped on the first car that signaled us to the train station. We didn’t have a minute to exchange money, buy food or get a map. Neither one of us had ever been to Morocco before. I wanted to get acquainted with this new place I had dreamt of visiting but we jumped from the taxi to the station and someone told us the train for Fez was leaving in 5 but we could catch the next one in a few hours. I though great, let’s finally take a breather, get some coffee and buy some dirhams but no, the wild one was already carrying the suitcases through the platform before I could stop him. He jumped on board the moving train and I only had time to jump behind him before the train completely left the station. 
RUN he said again, this time louder and with fear in his voice. 
So I picked up my bag and ran. I managed to flag a cab at the boarding area of the station, we entered quickly as I scrambled to the driver “conduire vite s’il te plait” to which he responded by pressing the accelerator to full speed. Part 3/3
With his face flushed from what I assume now was shame, he shared that in the confusion of being in a new country, desperation to pee, and inability to read signs properly he had used the toilet in the prayer room where people wash their hands, feet and face😫!!! Morocco is a Muslim country and the call to prayer is heard throughout the city multiple times a day. The most religious people stop what they are doing, wash themselves and pray. Many large public areas will have a place for people to wash themselves before prayer and the train station was no exception. This might come as surprise to people in secular countries but it’s common in Morocco. 
The attendant flagged the clueless man for his transgression which he had not yet noticed and instead of stopping to apologize and explain the situation he got embarrassed and started to walk away. And that’s when a crowd began to form to witness the commotion between him with broken English and the attendant speaking Arabic. I’d probably have joined the angry mob at that point, I was hungry, tired and mad AF, but we had already driven away towards the medina. It was getting late and no cars are allowed to navigate the 9000 plus maze like streets of the ancient city and I desperately needed to stop running. I wanted to arrive somewhere where I could relax for a minute and begin to experience  this country. It was then that I realized we both had made very big mistakes that day. Mine was agreeing to travel with someone I didn’t know so well🧳

He was 15. His name was Mario. 
He lived in the building next to mine and was oh so handsome. I secretly had a huge crush on him but was too embarrassed to even attempt eye contact. Both of our buildings faced the lake, Lagoa Rodrigo de Freitas, in Ipanema. That’s where I grew up. Girl from Ipanema. I’d see him walk home from the beach with his surfboard. 
Dreamy. One early evening out of the blue he rang my apt. Our maid told me there was a boy asking for Ana downstairs. I nearly fainted. He lived in the penthouse of his building. I lived in the third floor. His balcony had a bird’s eye view of mine. I’d spend too many hours after school pretending to look at the lake secretly wishing he’d show up at his balcony.  But whenever he did, and he always showed up, I’d duck and hide- face burning with embarrassment. I was eating dinner with my father but I jumped up a and quickly ran downstairs. My heart was pounding so strongly when we hugged I could feel my own heart pulsating through his chest. He held my hand and we went for a walk. He told me he also lived with his father. His parents were divorced like mine. He stopped at one point, I was perched higher on the edge of the sidewalk and he leaned in. I had never kissed anyone before. I was so nervous.  He kissed the right side of my cheek first. Gently. He knew what he was doing. Instead of enjoying the magical moment, this overthinking brain of mine was too preoccupied with looking like a fool. I desperately  didn’t want him to think I was a clueless girl who didn’t know how to kiss. He caressed my hair and pulled it off my shoulders. I was counting down in my head, eyes wide open like a deer watching a oncoming car driving north on I-95. His lips finally touched mine. Even my hands were sweating, I didn’t understand my lips were supposed to do. Afterwords, he looked at me and mumbled something like have you ever kissed before to which I nodded in way that said both yes and no but I had no words to speak of. We crossed the street back to our respective homes. I of course remained head over heels for Mario but that was our first and last kiss!

Have a seat while I prepare a caipirinha and tell you this story.
I was invited to chaperone a group of university students on a volunteer summer trip.
We flew into Guatemala City and then took 4 hr ride to this small village on the border of lake Atitlán. The volcan de fuego had erupted and we could see the smoke from the road. We arrived at our accommodations at night and got ready for a few days of volunteer work ahead. House building. Road paving. I was even invited to deliver a lecture on my research to the local school. I loved connecting with the students, visiting a new country, hearing different languages but there was something about this type of trip that didn’t sit well with me…

The students on the trip were wonderful. Respectful. Curious. Engaged. They organized the experience from beginning to end.
I was mostly there as the point of contact professor from our university. And 
I’m still in touch with a couple of students to this day.
But so many questions remain - who really benefits from these “volunteer” experiences ?
A group of students from the US visit a “poor” Latina American country for a week and then get to write about the experience in their grad school application or the locals who get their quotidian tasks disrupted by a group of foreigners?
Is this type of “help” truly beneficial to the local people ? 
In Judaism we have a word to refer to good deeds- mitzvah- and I very much believe in the importance of that, but deeds without the critical lens to highlight the dynamics of power, disruption and even reliance make me uncomfortable. Not that some of those issues weren’t part of our discussion during the trip, but the power dynamic of this type of volunteer experience remained unchallenged.
San Lucas Toliman is a beautiful small village and the locals were kind and incredibly welcoming. I am forever grateful for their hospitality but this visit still leaves me a bit unsettled.
I feel similarly about my dissertation, and many aspects of academia tbh but I will leave those stories for another day 🎓

A few things I struggle doing what I do now versus having a traditional job:
1. Spending so much time on my phone my eyes hurt 
2. Feeling pressured to document/keep up with the algorithm to stay relevant 
3. Deep fear that I can’t turn around one day to my previous life - I’m not sure I’d want to but having options is important to me 
4. Having to monitor my account for poachers/scammers/impersonators and haters constantly. Life would be easier if people created their own instead of trying to steal or destroy others
5. Lack of in person community. Social media work can be very lonely . There’s no faculty meeting. No office mates. Very little interaction with people in real life
6. Pressure to present perfection because every single person is filtered through 2 or 3 apps before their images are shared. The algorithm rewards beauty and the standards are not realistic - scroll to the second photo to see me without a filter. If that was my first photo this post would underperform even more. The closer to AI robots our images are, the higher the engagement. It’s just how this game works now. I do fear the ramifications of this deep disconnect between real life and social media images
7. Feeling pigeonholed in a particular category when I’d like to explore others  yet feeling trapped to the economic consequences of underperforming posts (I’ve already noticed a trend) that don’t cast me under the expected light when I do attempt something a bit “off brand”
- - - - - - - - - 
If you read this far, thank you! I appreciate you! If you are in a similar situation to me and would like to add, please go ahead. I’d love to hear more from you.
